All programmers strive to make their code easy to understand, but sometimes extra explanation is warranted. In these cases, programmers leave *comments* in their source code that the compiler will ignore but people reading the source code may find useful.

In Rust, the idiomatic comment style starts a comment with two slashes, and the comment continues until the end of the line. For comments that extend beyond a single line, you'll need to include `//` on each line:

```rust
// hello, world
```

```rust
// So we're doing something complicated here, long enough that we need
// multiple lines of comments to do it! Whew! Hopefully, this comment will
// explain what's going on.
```

Comments can also be placed at the end of lines containing code:

```rust
fn main() {
    let lucky_number = 7; // I'm feeling lucky today
}
```

But you'll more often see them used in this format, with the comment on a separate line above the code it's annotating:

```rust
fn main() {
    // I'm feeling lucky today
    let lucky_number = 7;
}
```

Rust also has another kind of comment, documentation comments, which we'll discuss in Chapter 14. Documentation comments use `///` and support Markdown notation for formatting the text. They're placed just before the item they document:

```rust
/// Adds one to the number given.
///
/// # Examples
///
/// ```
/// let arg = 5;
/// let answer = my_crate::add_one(arg);
/// assert_eq!(6, answer);
/// ```
pub fn add_one(x: i32) -> i32 {
    x + 1
}
```

There's also `//!` which adds documentation to the item that contains the comments, rather than to the items following the comments. This is typically used inside the crate root file (usually src/lib.rs) or inside a module to document the crate or the module as a whole.

codeExamples.code:
// This is a comment
fn main() {
    let x = 5; // this is also a comment
}

/// Adds one to the number given.
///
/// # Examples
///
/// ```
/// let answer = add_one(5);
/// assert_eq!(6, answer);
/// ```
pub fn add_one(x: i32) -> i32 {
    x + 1
}

